
# Matching desired characters

. - Any character except new line

\d  - Digit (0-9)

\D - Not a Digit

\w - Word character (a-z, A-Z, 0-9, _)

\W - Not a word character (space, tab, newline)

\s - whitespace (space, tab, newline)

\S - Not whitespace (space, tab, newline)

###########

# Boundaries, start and end of characters

\b - Word Boundary

\B - Not a word Boundary

^ - beginning of a string

$  - End of string

###########

# Character to set to match specific
# set of characters.

# '-' the hyphen inside a character set matches
# can be just the literal hyphen symbol,
# or if used between characters. [1-5], it
# [a-r]
# would match only numbers between 1 and 5.

[] - Matches Characters in brackets

[^ ] - Matches characters NOT in bracket

| - Either or

() - Group - allows us to match several different patterns

###########

# Quantifiers - use this to match more than one
# character at a time
# use this in conjunction with \d, or \w and so
# they quantify how many we want.

*      - 0 or more
+      - 1 or more
?      - 0 or One
{3}    - Exact number
{3, 4} - Range of Numbers (Minimum, Maximum)